2. ⚙️ Global Configuration with /setup
The /setup command defines the admin role, team role, and the bot status channel.
Only server administrators can use it.

Command: /setup

Parameters (all optional, but you’ll want to set them):

admin_role – The role that can use all bot commands (including /setup, /shutdown, /permit, etc.).

team_role – The role for your support team. Members with this role can manage tickets and use /embed-bot, but cannot change global settings.

status_channel – A text channel where Zypharion will post a live status embed (🟢 Online / 🔴 Offline).

Example:
/setup admin_role:@Admin team_role:@Moderator status_channel:#bot-status

After running the command, the bot will automatically send a status embed in the chosen channel, showing 🟢 Online.
The team role is also used as a fallback in the Ticket and Application systems if you don’t set specific roles there.

Resetting all settings:
/resetup – Deletes all configuration files (global, ticket, application, permissions, counters) and reverts the bot to its default state. Use this if you want to start fresh.

3. 🎫 Ticket System
Zypharion’s ticket system lets users create private support channels via a dropdown menu. Each ticket type can have its own name, role, and category.

3.1 Setting up Tickets with /ticket-setup
Only server administrators can use this command.

Command: /ticket-setup

Required parameters:

channel – The text channel where the ticket panel (dropdown) will be sent.

category – The category under which all ticket channels will be created.

Optional parameters (you can customize everything):

panel_title – Title of the panel embed (default: 🎟️ Support‑Tickets).

panel_description – Description text of the panel embed.

ticket_title – Title of the welcome embed inside the ticket channel.

ticket_description – Welcome message inside the ticket channel. Use {member} as placeholder for the user mention.

type1 to type9 – Names of up to 9 different ticket types (e.g., “General Support”, “Bug Report”).

role1 to role9 – Corresponding staff roles for each ticket type. Members with that role can see and manage tickets of that type. If no role is given, the global team_role is used as fallback.

Example:
/ticket-setup channel:#🎫-tickets category:Support type1:General Support role1:@Support-Team type2:Bug Report role2:@Dev-Team panel_title:Helpdesk

After execution:

The old panel message (if any) is deleted.

A new dropdown panel is sent to #🎫-tickets.

The config is saved; future ticket creations will use the settings.

3.2 How Users Create Tickets
Users click the dropdown in the panel and choose a ticket type.

A private channel is created under the configured category.

Only the user and the designated staff role (or fallback team role) can see the channel.

A welcome embed is posted, and the staff role is pinged.

Buttons appear: Close, Claim, Unclaim, Ping Staff.

3.3 Managing Tickets as Staff
Close – Opens a modal where you must enter a reason. The ticket channel is deleted after 10 seconds. The ticket creator receives a DM with the reason. (Only staff can close.)

Claim – Assign the ticket to yourself (only staff).

Unclaim – Release the ticket so another staff member can claim it.

Ping Staff – Only the ticket creator can use this. It pings the responsible role, but has a 10‑minute cooldown.

3.4 Additional Ticket Commands
/embed-send [channel] – (Staff only) Re‑sends the ticket panel to the same or a different channel.

/close – (Staff only) Closes the current ticket channel directly (opens the reason modal).

3.5 Resetting Tickets
/ticket-resetup – Deletes the panel message and resets all ticket settings (types, roles, category). Then you can run /ticket-setup again.

4. 📝 Application System
The application system lets users apply for staff positions via a DM questionnaire. You can customize questions, responses, and assign reviewers.

4.1 Setting up Applications with /application-setup
Only server administrators can use this.

Command: /application-setup

Required parameters:

panel_channel – Channel where the application panel (dropdown) will be sent.

target_channel – Channel where filled‑out applications will be posted for review.

Optional parameters (everything can be tailored):

required_role – A role a user must have to be able to submit an application.

forbidden_role – A role that, if present, prevents the user from applying.

type1 – Name of the application type (e.g., “Staff Application”).

role1 – Role that is allowed to review (accept/deny) applications of this type. If not set, admins can review.

panel_title – Title of the panel embed (default: 🌟 Bewerbungen).

panel_description – Description text of the panel embed.

submitted_title / submitted_description – DM sent to the applicant after they finish (use {user} as placeholder).

accepted_title / accepted_description – DM when accepted (use {user}, {type}, {server}, {reason}).

denied_title / denied_description – DM when denied.

q1 to q10 – Up to 10 custom questions asked in the DM.

Example:
/application-setup panel_channel:#📩-apply target_channel:#📋-applications type1:Staff Application role1:@Management required_role:@Member panel_title:Join Our Team q1:Why do you want to join? q2:What is your timezone?

After execution, a dropdown panel is posted in #📩-apply, and future applications will follow your settings.

4.2 How Users Apply
In the panel channel, users click the dropdown and select the application type.

They receive a DM with the first question. They answer, the bot asks the next, until all questions are done.

After each answer, the user sees how long they took (⏱️ *4.2 Sek.*).

When finished, a summary (with times) is sent to the target_channel and the applicant gets a confirmation DM.

In the review channel, staff members see ✅ Accept and ❌ Deny buttons.

4.3 Reviewing Applications
Accept – Opens a modal where the reviewer must enter a reason. The embed turns green and the applicant receives a DM with the reason.

Deny – Same, but embed turns red and the applicant is notified.

Only members with the designated review role (or admins) can use these buttons.

4.4 Additional Application Commands
/application-embed [channel] – Re‑sends the application panel to the given channel (or the saved one if omitted).

/application-resetup – Deletes the panel and resets all application settings.

5. 🛠️ Moderation & Utility Commands
5.1 /clear
Deletes a specified number of messages in the current channel.
Usage: /clear amount:50

amount – Number of messages (1‑100). Enter 0 to delete all messages (use with caution).

Permissions: Admins, team members, and users explicitly granted with /permit clear can use it. If a user has a limit (set via /permit), they cannot delete more than that limit.

5.2 /spam & /stop_spam
/spam text:Hello – Starts a continuous spam of the given text in the current channel. The bot sends as fast as Discord allows, automatically handling rate limits.
/stop_spam – Stops the spam in the current channel.

Both commands require the user to be permitted (admins/team can always use them).

Useful for testing, but please be mindful of other server members.

5.3 /permit, /revoke, /permit_list
Fine‑grained permission control for specific commands.

/permit user:@Username command:clear limit:30 – Allows a user to use /clear, but only up to 30 messages at a time.

/revoke user:@Username command:clear – Removes the permission for that command.

/permit_list [user] – Shows all permissions. If no user is given, it lists all users with special permissions.

Only server administrators can grant/revoke permissions.

5.4 /embed-bot [channel]
Sends or updates the bot’s status embed in the given channel. If no channel is provided, the one from /setup is used.

This embed automatically switches between 🟢 Online and 🔴 Offline when the bot starts/stops.

Team role (or admin) required.

5.5 /shutdown
Safely shuts down the bot.

Sets the status embed to 🔴 Offline, sends a goodbye message, and then disconnects.

Only server administrators can use this.

6. 📋 Viewing All Commands
Type /commands to see a beautifully formatted list of every slash command Zypharion offers, along with its description. This works for everyone.

7. 🔁 Complete Reset
/resetup (admin only) – Deletes all bot data, including:

Global config (admin role, team role, status channel)

Ticket config (panel, types, roles)

Application config (panel, questions, texts)

Permission overrides (/permit entries)

Ticket counter

After a reset, Zypharion is in its factory state – ready for a fresh setup.

